Background

In the data folder, you will find data about shark incidents in California between 1950-2022. The data are from: State of California- Shark Incident Database.

Load the libraries

library("tidyverse")
library("janitor")

Load the data

Run the following code chunk to import the data. In this chunk, I am removing NAs.

sharks <- 
  read_csv("data/SharkIncidents_1950_2022_220302.csv", 
           na=c("NA", "N/A", "Unknown", "NOT COUNTED", "", " ")) %>% 
  clean_names()

Questions

  1. Are there any hotspots for shark incidents in California? Show the top five counties with the most incidents.
sharks %>% 
  count(county) %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% 
  slice_head(n=5)
## # A tibble: 5  2
##   county            n
##   <chr>         <int>
## 1 San Diego        25
## 2 Humboldt         20
## 3 San Mateo        19
## 4 Santa Barbara    19
## 5 Marin            16
  1. Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents per county.
sharks %>% 
  count(county) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(county,n),y=n))+
  geom_col()+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title="Total Number of Incidents per County", y="Total Number of Incidents",x="County")

  1. Are there months of the year when incidents are more likely to occur? Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by month. Which month has the highest number of incidents?

October has the highest number of incidents.

  1. Is there a time of day when most attacks occur? Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by time of day. Which time of day has the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>% 
  count(time) %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=time,y=n))+
  geom_col()+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title="Total Number of Incidents per Time in a Day", y="Total Number of Incidents",x="Time")

11:00 has the highest number of incidents.

  1. Use the table from #5 to make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by county.
sharks %>% 
  select(county,injury) %>% 
  group_by(county) %>% 
  count(injury) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=county,y=n,fill=injury))+
  geom_col()+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title="Total number of incidents by county",x="County",y="Incidents")

  1. Make a plot that compares the number of incidents by activity.
sharks %>% 
  group_by(mode) %>% 
  count(mode) %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=mode,y=n))+
  geom_col()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=30,hjust=0.85))+
  labs(title="Number of incidents by activity",x="Activity Types",y="Incidents")

  1. Are all incidents involving Great Whites fatal? Make a plot that shows the number and types of incidents for Great Whites only.
sharks %>% 
  filter(species=="White") %>% 
  count(injury) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=injury,y=n))+
  geom_col()+
  labs(title="Incidents for Great White's only",x="Injury Types",y="Incidents")

Not all of the Great White incidents are fatal. In fact, fatal is only a small portion.
